# QtWidgets Rules

- Keep widgets focused on presentation and interaction. Do not put package-manager business logic or command construction in UI code; use the view-model and `UiLoader` (worker thread) for data loading.
- Bind widgets to view-model properties, signals, and slots. Prefer unidirectional flow: user action → view-model request signal → loader (worker) → result signal → view-model updates models → widgets reflect state.
- Represent package operations with explicit states (idle, loading, success, failed). Show progress, disable conflicting actions, and make cancellation/retry paths obvious.
- Surface risky actions clearly (remove, downgrade, orphan cleanup, cache cleanup, AUR install). Require explicit user confirmation before destructive operations.
- Keep reusable UI pieces modular: main window, sidebar, package list, details pane, and page widgets under `ui/pages/` and `ui/widgets/`.
- Do not call services or backends directly from widget code; always go through the view-model and async loader so the UI thread never blocks on package data.
- When adding new screens, preserve the distinction between repo and AUR packages and use the existing controller/repository layer for loading.
